\begin{abstract}
Healthcare navigation is often challenging for patients due to difficulties in describing symptoms, understanding insurance networks, and identifying appropriate healthcare providers. This project presents \textit{Appy Health}, an AI-powered conversational system designed to guide patients through symptom reporting and automatically match them with suitable healthcare providers. The system integrates a large language model (LLM) with structured provider data to support symptom understanding, missing information detection, and provider recommendation. The prototype uses a React-based conversational interface, a FastAPI backend, and OpenAI GPT-4.1 for language reasoning. Provider matching is performed through hard constraints (e.g., specialty and insurance compatibility) and soft scoring factors (e.g., distance and availability). A synthetic dataset containing provider and patient scenarios was used to evaluate system behavior across multiple cases. Results demonstrate that the system can correctly guide patient conversations and produce clinically reasonable provider recommendations.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Navigating healthcare systems can be difficult for many patients. Individuals often struggle to clearly describe symptoms, determine which type of medical specialist they should consult, and identify providers who accept their insurance plans.

Large language models (LLMs) create new opportunities for improving healthcare navigation through conversational interfaces. LLMs can interpret natural language symptom descriptions, extract structured information, and guide users through step-by-step interactions.

In this project, we develop \textit{Appy Health}, a prototype conversational system that assists patients in identifying appropriate healthcare providers. The system collects symptom descriptions through dialogue, identifies missing information through follow-up questions, and performs provider matching using structured healthcare data.

